Tornadoes

Next we turn our attention to tornadoes.

Tornadoes occur seemly random across the country. A first step to understanding them is to map where they occur.

There are many ways to make a map with R. One easy way is with the functions in ggmap. Let’s begin by making a map of the campus.

The first line of code makes the functions from ggmap available. The second line uses the geocode() function to locate the Bellamy Building.

library("ggmap")
## Loading required package: ggplot2
loc = geocode("Bellamy Building Florida State University")
## Information from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=Bellamy%20Building%20Florida%20State%20University&sensor=false
loc
##        lon      lat
## 1 -84.2958 30.44345

Next we use the get_map() function to call the google map server and center the map on loc. The map is saved in the object called Map.

Map = get_map(location = loc, 
              source = "google",
              zoom = 15,
              color = "bw",
              maptype = "terrain")
## Map from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=30.443447,-84.295803&zoom=15&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=terrain&language=en-EN&sensor=false

Finally we use the ggmap() function to render the map to the display.

ggmap(Map, dev = "extent") +
    labs(x = expression(paste("Longitude (", degree, "W)")), 
       y = expression(paste("Latitude (", degree, "N)")))

Easy!

Try making a map of Tallahassee or your home town.
